my opinion of studies

00:40:37.498 --> 00:40:39.130
that equate the
intelligence of animals

00:40:39.130 --> 00:40:42.606
with humans at certain ages.

00:40:42.606 --> 00:40:44.105
Well, in a way,
they're interesting.

00:40:44.105 --> 00:40:47.070
And in a way, they're
the wrong question.

00:40:47.070 --> 00:40:51.660
And I came to see that it's
the wrong question because I

00:40:51.660 --> 00:40:54.300
asked Cynthia Moss, who
has been studying elephants

00:40:54.300 --> 00:40:56.260
for 40 years.

00:40:56.260 --> 00:40:58.190
This, I thought, was
the big question.

00:40:58.190 --> 00:41:03.480
I said, what has watching
elephants for 40 years taught

00:41:03.480 --> 00:41:05.870
you about human nature?

00:41:05.870 --> 00:41:08.410
And I thought that was
a really deep question,

00:41:08.410 --> 00:41:11.650
and it was going to be so
interesting to talk about.

00:41:11.650 --> 00:41:15.340
And she said, I'm not
really interested in that.

00:41:15.340 --> 00:41:17.390
I'm interested in elephants.

00:41:17.390 --> 00:41:19.160
I want to learn about elephants.

00:41:19.160 --> 00:41:24.810
Comparing an elephant or a
raven's performance on a puzzle

00:41:24.810 --> 00:41:29.260
to a human toddler doesn't
interest me at all.

00:41:29.260 --> 00:41:31.980
And I was very
taken aback by that.

00:41:31.980 --> 00:41:35.000
I also felt kind of stupid
for asking that question,

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:36.850
considering her response.

00:41:36.850 --> 00:41:38.300
And I thought about that.

00:41:38.300 --> 00:41:43.870
It took me a few days for me to
really do a full mental reset

00:41:43.870 --> 00:41:45.080
on that question.

00:41:45.080 --> 00:41:47.660
The problem with
comparing a raven

00:41:47.660 --> 00:41:50.330
to a toddler or
the communication

00:41:50.330 --> 00:41:56.090
ability of a chimpanzee
to a small child

00:41:56.090 --> 00:41:59.560
is not that it
tells you nothing,

00:41:59.560 --> 00:42:01.700
but that it doesn't
ask the question that

00:42:01.700 --> 00:42:03.570
lets you get the full answer.

00:42:03.570 --> 00:42:05.650
It's always about us.

00:42:05.650 --> 00:42:09.880
Tell me, what could you learn
about the ability of a raven

00:42:09.880 --> 00:42:12.830
to solve a puzzle by
comparing it with a child?

00:42:12.830 --> 00:42:15.360
You learn, again,
that humans are better

00:42:15.360 --> 00:42:18.700
at solving puzzles than ravens.

00:42:18.700 --> 00:42:21.450
But you don't really
learn a lot about what

00:42:21.450 --> 00:42:25.625
ravens do in their
complicated, vivid lives

00:42:25.625 --> 00:42:29.820
that they lead among their
friends and their rivals

00:42:29.820 --> 00:42:33.820
in familiar territories,
how they seek status, how

00:42:33.820 --> 00:42:36.860
their status gets deposed over
the course of their life, how

00:42:36.860 --> 00:42:39.090
their life follows
the arc of a career.

00:42:39.090 --> 00:42:40.690
You don't learn any
of that about them

00:42:40.690 --> 00:42:43.140
by comparing them
to a three-year-old.

00:42:43.140 --> 00:42:46.420
So the whole question
of what intelligence

00:42:46.420 --> 00:42:49.380
is, is a very
fraught definitional

00:42:49.380 --> 00:42:52.140
question anyway,
because there are just

00:42:52.140 --> 00:42:53.690
different kinds of capacities.

00:42:53.690 --> 00:42:56.290
And usually with
humans, we think

00:42:56.290 --> 00:43:00.730
of intelligence, more
or less, as the ability

00:43:00.730 --> 00:43:04.780
to solve novel problems.

00:43:04.780 --> 00:43:07.730
And many humans have
a pretty good ability

00:43:07.730 --> 00:43:09.310
to solve novel problems.

00:43:09.310 --> 00:43:14.070
But who was more intelligent,
Henry Ford or Pablo Picasso?

00:43:14.070 --> 00:43:17.835
Does intelligence mean
anything at most levels

00:43:17.835 --> 00:43:20.240
of performance and existence?

00:43:20.240 --> 00:43:23.610
And many animals do things
that we can't do at all.

00:43:23.610 --> 00:43:26.000
But if we can do anything,
we give ourselves

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:28.200
an enormous amount of credit.

00:43:28.200 --> 00:43:30.317
Like we have the
ability to learn music,

00:43:30.317 --> 00:43:32.150
for instance, just to
think of one thing off

00:43:32.150 --> 00:43:33.160
the top of my head.

00:43:33.160 --> 00:43:36.560
We can learn music, and we can
learn how to play instruments

00:43:36.560 --> 00:43:39.610
that other people have invented
for us to play and make music.

00:43:39.610 --> 00:43:41.050
We just have a musical ability.

00:43:41.050 --> 00:43:43.830
We don't have such a
great homing ability.

00:43:43.830 --> 00:43:46.220
We can't home for
thousands of miles

00:43:46.220 --> 00:43:49.770
across open ocean just
based on our perception

00:43:49.770 --> 00:43:52.070
of the Earth's magnetic
field, and things like that.

00:43:52.070 --> 00:43:56.050
So fish and birds that can do
that, we just discount that.

00:43:56.050 --> 00:43:59.250
We don't say, oh, my god,
they're brilliant at this.

00:43:59.250 --> 00:44:01.140
They are geniuses
compared to us.

00:44:01.140 --> 00:44:01.990
We never say that.

00:44:01.990 --> 00:44:04.512
We just say, oh, who cares?

00:44:04.512 --> 00:44:06.500
Well, we can play
an instrument, or we

00:44:06.500 --> 00:44:09.170
can solve a problem,
or something like that.

00:44:09.170 --> 00:44:12.190
There have been experiments
done with ravens,

00:44:12.190 --> 00:44:15.891
with certain kinds of puzzles,
where the ravens can figure it

00:44:15.891 --> 00:44:16.390
out.

00:44:16.390 --> 00:44:20.050
And dogs and toddlers are left,
in the words of one researcher,

00:44:20.050 --> 00:44:23.020
"not even realizing there
was a puzzle to solve."

00:44:23.020 --> 00:44:27.870
So to me, it just isn't
really all about us,

00:44:27.870 --> 00:44:29.054
and it's not all about now.

00:44:29.054 --> 00:44:30.720
And we have to get
outside of ourselves.

00:44:30.720 --> 00:44:32.840
Every time, we're always
looking at the world

00:44:32.840 --> 00:44:34.570
through our eyes,
which of course is

00:44:34.570 --> 00:44:36.770
the normal starting place.

00:44:36.770 --> 00:44:38.720
But when you look
from the inside out,

00:44:38.720 --> 00:44:41.410
you only can see an
inside out world.

00:44:41.410 --> 00:44:44.090
When you can get
outside yourself,

00:44:44.090 --> 00:44:46.935
like the famous iconic
first photograph

00:44:46.935 --> 00:44:52.420
of Earth from space orbit, you
get a different perspective.

00:44:52.420 --> 00:44:55.560
And what I've really tried to
do in my work, in my thinking,

00:44:55.560 --> 00:44:59.000
and this book is get
outside of ourselves

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:01.710
and look at humans
in perspective,

00:45:01.710 --> 00:45:06.110
in the whole sweep of life, and
the history of life on Earth,

00:45:06.110 --> 00:45:08.920
and the whole family of living
things that are here with us.

00:45:08.920 --> 00:45:10.410
Because there's a lot at stake.

00:45:10.410 --> 00:45:14.510
And not only is there
a need, I think,

00:45:14.510 --> 00:45:18.610
to show what is at
stake as we take

00:45:18.610 --> 00:45:20.430
more and more from
the rest of the world,

00:45:20.430 --> 00:45:25.140
but I wanted to show
also who is at stake.

00:45:25.140 --> 00:45:26.770
Yes.

00:45:26.770 --> 00:45:29.391
AUDIENCE: Do you think animals,
like a dog sitting next

00:45:29.391 --> 00:45:34.990
to a windowsill, can daydream
and have thoughts unassociated

00:45:34.990 --> 00:45:37.030
to what they see?

00:45:37.030 --> 00:45:38.740
CARL SAFINA: Do I
think animals have

00:45:38.740 --> 00:45:41.520
daydreams and thoughts
unassociated from what

00:45:41.520 --> 00:45:42.520
they're actually seeing?

00:45:42.520 --> 00:45:46.360
Yeah, sometimes they do.

00:45:46.360 --> 00:45:48.540
And I see that in my own dogs.

00:45:48.540 --> 00:45:50.680
Sometimes my dogs
might be lying around.

00:45:50.680 --> 00:45:52.802
And then they'll
suddenly get up,

00:45:52.802 --> 00:45:54.760
and they'll run outside
to go and check and see

00:45:54.760 --> 00:45:56.360
if there are any squirrels
at the bird feeder.

00:45:56.360 --> 00:45:58.026
Because they love
chasing swirls around.

00:45:58.026 --> 00:45:59.620
So things occur to them.

00:45:59.620 --> 00:46:01.615
Sometimes they get up
and they come over.

00:46:01.615 --> 00:46:06.150
If I'm writing, and the
dog is napping nicely,

00:46:06.150 --> 00:46:08.587
they'll sometimes wake up,
especially one of them.

00:46:08.587 --> 00:46:10.420
She'll wake up, she'll
come, and she'll just

00:46:10.420 --> 00:46:11.890
start hitting me with her paw.

00:46:11.890 --> 00:46:13.554
And the door is open.

00:46:13.554 --> 00:46:14.470
So what does she want?

00:46:14.470 --> 00:46:17.570
She's just thought that she
wants me to go out with her.

00:46:17.570 --> 00:46:19.070
She wants to maybe go for a run.

00:46:19.070 --> 00:46:23.420
She's trying to get me to engage
with her, because these things

00:46:23.420 --> 00:46:24.846
cross her mind.

00:46:24.846 --> 00:46:27.310
If she could never think
about going for a run

00:46:27.310 --> 00:46:29.210
unless we were
going for a run, she

00:46:29.210 --> 00:46:31.390
wouldn't be coming and
bothering me to go for a run.

00:46:35.364 --> 00:46:37.030
Well, yeah, we'll
just leave it at that.

00:46:37.030 --> 00:46:38.990
I can tell you other stories,
but it's more or less

00:46:38.990 --> 00:46:39.580
the same point.

00:46:39.580 --> 00:46:40.010
Yes.

00:46:40.010 --> 00:46:41.760
AUDIENCE: So outside
of humans as animals,

00:46:41.760 --> 00:46:43.850
did you observe that some
of these other animals,

00:46:43.850 --> 00:46:46.490
the same species, would develop
different cultures depending

00:46:46.490 --> 00:46:48.130
on where they were?

00:46:48.130 --> 00:46:50.570
CARL SAFINA: Some animals do
develop different cultures

00:46:50.570 --> 00:46:52.400
depending on where they were.

00:46:52.400 --> 00:46:56.906
A couple of the most notable are
killer whales and chimpanzees.

00:46:59.920 --> 00:47:04.990
Chimpanzees make simple tools.

00:47:04.990 --> 00:47:07.920
But the tools they
make are different

00:47:07.920 --> 00:47:11.290
in different populations
of chimpanzees.

00:47:11.290 --> 00:47:14.455
So there are some chimpanzees
that fish for termites

00:47:14.455 --> 00:47:16.650
by using twigs and
pieces of grass.

00:47:16.650 --> 00:47:18.940
They stick it in
the termite hole,

00:47:18.940 --> 00:47:21.134
and the termites bite it
to try to defend the hole.

00:47:21.134 --> 00:47:22.800
And then they pull
it out, and then they

00:47:22.800 --> 00:47:24.710
eat the termites, right?

00:47:24.710 --> 00:47:26.610
Some of the chimpanzees
that do that live in

00:47:26.610 --> 00:47:31.120
places where there are really
hard nuts, and there are rocks.

00:47:31.120 --> 00:47:34.310
But they have never
figured out that you

00:47:34.310 --> 00:47:36.030
can use rocks to crack nuts.

00:47:36.030 --> 00:47:38.700
But there are other
chimpanzees that

00:47:38.700 --> 00:47:41.090
use rocks to crack
nuts all the time

00:47:41.090 --> 00:47:43.110
and actually use
rocks on another rock

00:47:43.110 --> 00:47:45.510
like an anvil to crack nuts.

00:47:45.510 --> 00:47:48.550
Those ones that have figured
that out have an advantage.

00:47:48.550 --> 00:47:51.060
They get more calories because
they have a whole other food

00:47:51.060 --> 00:47:52.640
source that's available to them.

00:47:52.640 --> 00:47:54.640
So they learn it
from one another.

00:47:54.640 --> 00:47:57.010
That's the definition
of culture.

00:47:57.010 --> 00:47:58.360
They're not born that way.

00:47:58.360 --> 00:47:59.840
They learn from one another.

00:47:59.840 --> 00:48:01.920
But the other population
doesn't have it yet.

00:48:01.920 --> 00:48:04.455
So when you think
about humans, you

00:48:04.455 --> 00:48:08.580
have to try to think of before
globalization of any kind,

00:48:08.580 --> 00:48:12.620
before ships got
all around anyplace.

00:48:12.620 --> 00:48:14.850
Human cultures were often
very, very different

00:48:14.850 --> 00:48:15.640
from one another.

00:48:15.640 --> 00:48:17.639
The technologies were
often very, very different

00:48:17.639 --> 00:48:18.420
from one another.

00:48:18.420 --> 00:48:21.400
So you see the inkling
of that in chimpanzees

00:48:21.400 --> 00:48:24.470
with simple tools.

00:48:24.470 --> 00:48:27.690
And those chimps have
stone and anvils.

00:48:27.690 --> 00:48:30.820
And some of them have
wooden clubs and anvils.

00:48:30.820 --> 00:48:36.170
That's not terribly dissimilar
to the most advanced tools

00:48:36.170 --> 00:48:41.810
that many people had until
recently, not that long ago,

00:48:41.810 --> 00:48:44.237
where there are many cultures
where the most advanced tool

00:48:44.237 --> 00:48:45.070
was a bow and arrow.

00:48:45.070 --> 00:48:46.527
They had no machine of any kind.

00:48:46.527 --> 00:48:48.360
They had nothing that
had an internal moving

00:48:48.360 --> 00:48:50.040
part of any kind.

00:48:50.040 --> 00:48:53.730
They mostly had digging
sticks, and they had pounders,

00:48:53.730 --> 00:48:56.910
and they had spears,
and bows, and arrows.

00:48:56.910 --> 00:48:58.790
So anyway, that's chimpanzees.

00:48:58.790 --> 00:49:01.510
And with killer whales,
the cultural differences

00:49:01.510 --> 00:49:04.430
are strange.

00:49:04.430 --> 00:49:08.670
One is they have vocal
cultural differences.

00:49:08.670 --> 00:49:12.120
But the strange part is
that different groups have

00:49:12.120 --> 00:49:15.870
some of the same calls, some
calls specific to their group

00:49:15.870 --> 00:49:17.020
only.

00:49:17.020 --> 00:49:19.270
Other groups they
socialize with do not

00:49:19.270 --> 00:49:22.730
pick up on the calls
of that other group.

00:49:22.730 --> 00:49:24.939
It helps to define
which group is which.

00:49:24.939 --> 00:49:26.980
And even though they
mingle, and even though they

00:49:26.980 --> 00:49:29.870
hear each other, they
don't copy all of those

00:49:29.870 --> 00:49:32.525
sounds that clearly
those ones in the groups

00:49:32.525 --> 00:49:35.160
learn from the other ones.

00:49:35.160 --> 00:49:40.260
And some of the groups mingle.

00:49:40.260 --> 00:49:45.230
And some of the groups get close
to each other and never meet.

00:49:45.230 --> 00:49:48.450
and never mingle,
like ethnic groups

00:49:48.450 --> 00:49:51.910
that don't like each
other for some reason.

00:49:51.910 --> 00:49:55.110
And it's not explained,
but it's a weird thing.

00:49:55.110 --> 00:49:58.090
And the closest thing to
what those killer whales do

00:49:58.090 --> 00:50:02.170
is humans, where there
are different tribes that

00:50:02.170 --> 00:50:04.330
won't mix even though
we're all exactly

00:50:04.330 --> 00:50:07.730
the same, except for
small cultural or language

00:50:07.730 --> 00:50:08.230
differences.

00:50:08.230 --> 00:50:10.144
It's mostly where you're
born is what it is.

00:50:10.144 --> 00:50:11.560
And with those
killer whales, it's

00:50:11.560 --> 00:50:15.400
mostly where they're born,
what pod they're born into.

00:50:15.400 --> 00:50:18.310
And they carry that identity,
and they won't mix with others.

00:50:18.310 --> 00:50:20.602
And it's very odd.

00:50:20.602 --> 00:50:21.435
Any other questions?

00:50:21.435 --> 00:50:21.934
Richard.

00:50:21.934 --> 00:50:22.570
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:50:22.570 --> 00:50:27.197
By the way, that's similar
to certain jungle birds.

00:50:27.197 --> 00:50:29.430
And they'll go into
these big, mixed flocks.

00:50:29.430 --> 00:50:32.790
And they will pay
attention to warning cries

00:50:32.790 --> 00:50:35.190
of predators from another
species or another group.

00:50:35.190 --> 00:50:37.110
And but then they will
segregate out again,

00:50:37.110 --> 00:50:38.365
so it's very similar.

00:50:38.365 --> 00:50:39.990
The question I want
to ask you is this.

00:50:39.990 --> 00:50:40.990
You say you kept wolves.

00:50:40.990 --> 00:50:43.590
I didn't know that
you kept wolves.

00:50:43.590 --> 00:50:44.340
CARL SAFINA: What?

00:50:44.340 --> 00:50:44.980
AUDIENCE: Wolves.

00:50:44.980 --> 00:50:46.688
CARL SAFINA: I didn't
keep wolves myself.

00:50:46.688 --> 00:50:47.775
No, no, I have dogs.

00:50:47.775 --> 00:50:48.850
AUDIENCE: Oh, OK.

00:50:48.850 --> 00:50:50.115
Well OK, I have dogs.

00:50:50.115 --> 00:50:54.856
And one thing that
I've read recently

00:50:54.856 --> 00:50:57.844
is that one of the innate
differences-- and I'm

00:50:57.844 --> 00:51:01.330
asking you if you know
whether this is true or not--

00:51:01.330 --> 00:51:08.875
between dogs and wolves is
that dogs will follow a human's

00:51:08.875 --> 00:51:10.612
gaze looking at something.

00:51:10.612 --> 00:51:11.320
CARL SAFINA: Yes.

00:51:11.320 --> 00:51:13.870
And right, and you're going to
say, and wolves don't, right?

00:51:13.870 --> 00:51:14.480
MALE SPEAKER: And wolves don't.

00:51:14.480 --> 00:51:15.360
CARL SAFINA: That's baloney.

00:51:15.360 --> 00:51:15.890
MALE SPEAKER: OK.

00:51:15.890 --> 00:51:17.598
CARL SAFINA: And here's
why it's baloney.

00:51:17.598 --> 00:51:20.290
And here's why a lot of the
laboratory studies of animals

00:51:20.290 --> 00:51:24.940
and animal behavior are
too simplistic to capture

00:51:24.940 --> 00:51:25.860
what's there.

00:51:25.860 --> 00:51:30.600
Dogs were tested to follow
pointing with their owners,

00:51:30.600 --> 00:51:32.810
the people they knew the best.

00:51:32.810 --> 00:51:34.750
So you take your dog into a lab.

00:51:34.750 --> 00:51:37.890
And they say, OK, you stand
there, and put the dog there.

00:51:37.890 --> 00:51:38.930
OK, sit.

00:51:38.930 --> 00:51:40.790
OK, ready, go.

00:51:40.790 --> 00:51:42.020
Now, point.

00:51:42.020 --> 00:51:44.050
OK, so the owner points.

00:51:44.050 --> 00:51:45.780
The dog looks.

00:51:45.780 --> 00:51:48.190
Then they take
wolves with humans

00:51:48.190 --> 00:51:49.551
that they don't know it all.

00:51:49.551 --> 00:51:52.050
They put them behind a chain
link fence because, oh, my god,

00:51:52.050 --> 00:51:53.500
they're wolves.

00:51:53.500 --> 00:51:54.330
And they point.

00:51:54.330 --> 00:51:56.980
And a wolf behind a chain link
fence surrounded by strangers

00:51:56.980 --> 00:51:59.490
doesn't look where the
other person is pointing.

00:51:59.490 --> 00:52:01.180
But it turns out
that when you take

00:52:01.180 --> 00:52:03.630
hand raised wolves
with familiar people,

00:52:03.630 --> 00:52:06.060
without a chain link fence
between them, and you point,

00:52:06.060 --> 00:52:08.740
the wolves perform
as well or better

00:52:08.740 --> 00:52:11.220
than the dogs with no training.

00:52:11.220 --> 00:52:14.280
Because they are
incredibly keyed into one

00:52:14.280 --> 00:52:16.250
another in their social groups.

00:52:16.250 --> 00:52:19.130
When a wolf goes like
that, all the other wolves

00:52:19.130 --> 00:52:21.410
have to see what's
interesting over there.

00:52:21.410 --> 00:52:22.920
Are we about to hunt?

00:52:22.920 --> 00:52:24.310
Did they just see something?

00:52:24.310 --> 00:52:25.050
What's going on?

00:52:25.050 --> 00:52:27.310
AUDIENCE: Well, the claim was
that that they did not do that.

00:52:27.310 --> 00:52:28.520
CARL SAFINA: The
claim is disproven.

00:52:28.520 --> 00:52:29.130
MALE SPEAKER: Good.

00:52:29.130 --> 00:52:30.320
CARL SAFINA: Put a
big X on that claim.

00:52:30.320 --> 00:52:31.437
One more question, yes.

00:52:31.437 --> 00:52:33.103
AUDIENCE: It's actually
related to that.

00:52:33.103 --> 00:52:35.803
You're talking-- there's
blurb about your book

00:52:35.803 --> 00:52:39.486
where you describe these
cooperative hunting behaviors,

00:52:39.486 --> 00:52:42.680
like whales knocking a seal
off an ice floe and lions

00:52:42.680 --> 00:52:44.123
attacking in wings.

00:52:44.123 --> 00:52:45.566
How does that
communication work?

00:52:45.566 --> 00:52:47.971
Do we know about
how they coordinate

00:52:47.971 --> 00:52:50.390
those kind of things?

00:52:50.390 --> 00:52:52.740
CARL SAFINA: In
some cases, we know.

00:52:52.740 --> 00:52:57.210
And I would say in most
cases we pretty much know.

00:52:57.210 --> 00:53:02.330
And that is, they're very,
very tuned into one another.

00:53:02.330 --> 00:53:05.630
So you mentioned the
killer whales that

00:53:05.630 --> 00:53:06.850
wash the seals off the ice.

00:53:06.850 --> 00:53:08.370
What was the other thing
that you mentioned?

00:53:08.370 --> 00:53:08.980
AUDIENCE: The lions.

00:53:08.980 --> 00:53:10.230
CARL SAFINA: The lions, right.

00:53:10.230 --> 00:53:13.170
So I actually saw some of
the thing with the lions.

00:53:13.170 --> 00:53:19.260
And I didn't see the behavior
develop because they knew

00:53:19.260 --> 00:53:21.160
exactly what they were doing.

00:53:21.160 --> 00:53:22.250
But I saw them do it.

00:53:22.250 --> 00:53:26.536
So what I saw was
lions are sleeping.

00:53:26.536 --> 00:53:27.660
We're watching these lions.

00:53:27.660 --> 00:53:29.350
We were watching
those particular lions

00:53:29.350 --> 00:53:32.310
because that particular
pride had a habit of hunting

00:53:32.310 --> 00:53:33.870
during daylight,
which is unusual.

00:53:33.870 --> 00:53:36.110
So we went to watch and
see if they were going

00:53:36.110 --> 00:53:37.910
to do something really cool.

00:53:37.910 --> 00:53:39.980
And they were sleeping,
and then they woke up.

00:53:39.980 --> 00:53:41.960
And when they woke
up, they got up

00:53:41.960 --> 00:53:45.560
and they did a big rally with
each other, a big greeting.

00:53:45.560 --> 00:53:47.420
They're all licking
each other's faces,

00:53:47.420 --> 00:53:50.720
and they're all smushing their
faces together and everything.

00:53:50.720 --> 00:53:52.580
And then they're
going to go hunt.

00:53:52.580 --> 00:53:56.470
Now, first of all, you don't
need to lick somebody's face

00:53:56.470 --> 00:53:58.360
in order to go hunting, right?

00:53:58.360 --> 00:53:59.570
But they do that.

00:53:59.570 --> 00:54:00.410
Why do they do that?

00:54:00.410 --> 00:54:02.530
Because that's a reaffirmation.

00:54:02.530 --> 00:54:04.920
It's just like we wake up
and we say good morning

00:54:04.920 --> 00:54:06.500
to everybody in our family.

00:54:06.500 --> 00:54:08.070
It's a reaffirmation.

00:54:08.070 --> 00:54:08.710
We're here.

00:54:08.710 --> 00:54:10.130
We know who we are.

00:54:10.130 --> 00:54:11.060
We're together.

00:54:11.060 --> 00:54:12.880
This is our group identity.

00:54:12.880 --> 00:54:18.100
So that thing, reestablished
in the course of their day,

00:54:18.100 --> 00:54:21.080
they then leave the
area where they were all

00:54:21.080 --> 00:54:22.470
lying around sleeping.

00:54:22.470 --> 00:54:24.960
And they leave together,
because that greeting

00:54:24.960 --> 00:54:26.230
helped coordinate them.

00:54:26.230 --> 00:54:27.400
OK, we're all up now?

00:54:27.400 --> 00:54:29.500
OK, let's go.

00:54:29.500 --> 00:54:31.430
They go to a hill.

00:54:31.430 --> 00:54:33.370
Obviously, they know
exactly what hill

00:54:33.370 --> 00:54:35.670
they're going to because
they just went there.

00:54:35.670 --> 00:54:37.050
They just go to the hill.

00:54:37.050 --> 00:54:42.470
And then they walk along
the crest of the hill.

00:54:42.470 --> 00:54:44.690
One of them sits down,
and the others keep going.

00:54:44.690 --> 00:54:47.405
And why did that lion just sit
down and the other keep going?

00:54:47.405 --> 00:54:50.830
A second lion sits down,
and the rest keep going.

00:54:50.830 --> 00:54:52.240
A third lion sits.

00:54:52.240 --> 00:54:55.340
A fourth lion sits,
until there is a picket

00:54:55.340 --> 00:54:57.630
fence of yellow lions
in the yellow grass

00:54:57.630 --> 00:54:58.900
at the crest of this hill.

00:54:58.900 --> 00:55:03.250
And one lion walks
toward the zebras that

00:55:03.250 --> 00:55:05.400
are about a quarter mile away.

00:55:05.400 --> 00:55:10.300
And the plan is-- which
they've obviously done before

00:55:10.300 --> 00:55:11.800
and they knew exactly
what they were

00:55:11.800 --> 00:55:14.410
doing-- we'll all wait here.

00:55:14.410 --> 00:55:17.310
You go chase the
zebras up the hill.

00:55:17.310 --> 00:55:18.770
The zebras were no fools.

00:55:18.770 --> 00:55:21.430
They detected the
lion that was coming,

00:55:21.430 --> 00:55:24.316
and they spooked and
went farther away.

00:55:24.316 --> 00:55:26.190
So what I saw was really,
really interesting,

00:55:26.190 --> 00:55:29.410
It wasn't incredibly dramatic
because the hunt really

00:55:29.410 --> 00:55:31.330
didn't engage.

00:55:31.330 --> 00:55:35.004
As far as the killer
whales, they fan out,

00:55:35.004 --> 00:55:37.170
and they're looking in the
pack ice, those ones that

00:55:37.170 --> 00:55:38.190
wash the seals off.

00:55:38.190 --> 00:55:40.670
They fan out, and they're
looking around the pack ice.

00:55:40.670 --> 00:55:43.890
They can hear each other a
long distance underwater,

00:55:43.890 --> 00:55:46.500
and they call a lot.

00:55:46.500 --> 00:55:48.830
They recognize each
other's voices,

00:55:48.830 --> 00:55:50.640
like you recognize
people on the telephone.

00:55:50.640 --> 00:55:52.600
They know who's
calling underwater.

00:55:52.600 --> 00:55:55.320
And they're looking
mostly for Weddell seals.

00:55:55.320 --> 00:55:58.410
It's a certain kind of seal
that they particularly like.

00:55:58.410 --> 00:56:00.800
So if they're not
food stressed, they're

00:56:00.800 --> 00:56:02.890
looking for Weddell seals.

00:56:02.890 --> 00:56:05.860
One of them finds
a Weddell seal.

00:56:05.860 --> 00:56:08.845
It doesn't immediately try
to attack the Weddell seal.

00:56:08.845 --> 00:56:14.120
It backs off and calls until
the rest of the group which

00:56:14.120 --> 00:56:16.660
might, in that case, be
three or four individuals,

00:56:16.660 --> 00:56:17.890
they all come together.

00:56:17.890 --> 00:56:20.850
They swim away from the ice.

00:56:20.850 --> 00:56:26.040
And then on some signal, either
vocal or visual behavioral,

00:56:26.040 --> 00:56:28.830
it's OK, now, and
then they all go.

00:56:28.830 --> 00:56:32.260
And they all pump their
tails like this in unison,

00:56:32.260 --> 00:56:36.430
and that creates a big moving
wave right above the tails.

00:56:36.430 --> 00:56:38.560
And they go right
to the ice, and then

00:56:38.560 --> 00:56:39.990
they just dive under the ice.

00:56:39.990 --> 00:56:41.900
That wave breaks over the ice.

00:56:41.900 --> 00:56:45.380
It washes the seal off, and
then they get the seal that way.

00:56:45.380 --> 00:56:49.950
And killer whales, more than
any other animal in the world,

00:56:49.950 --> 00:56:50.950
they share their kills.

00:56:50.950 --> 00:56:53.900
They share a really high
percentage of their kills.

00:56:53.900 --> 00:56:57.550
So it's a really, really
cooperative hunting thing.

00:56:57.550 --> 00:57:00.520
I mean, wolves share the kills
too but in a more passive way.

00:57:00.520 --> 00:57:02.540
The thing is down,
and it's just there,

00:57:02.540 --> 00:57:04.080
and they all eat from it.

00:57:04.080 --> 00:57:08.660
But the whales actually pull
it apart and bring pieces

00:57:08.660 --> 00:57:10.740
and give to one another.

00:57:10.740 --> 00:57:13.230
Because they're in a more
fluid environment like that.

00:57:13.230 --> 00:57:15.832
So I'm happy to stay
a few more minutes.

00:57:15.832 --> 00:57:17.540
I don't want to keep
you too much longer,

00:57:17.540 --> 00:57:19.550
because we did start late.

00:57:19.550 --> 00:57:21.920
And I want to thank you very,
very much for coming out.

00:57:21.920 --> 00:57:22.820
Obviously, we've got
some books in the back.

00:57:22.820 --> 00:57:23.720
Thank you.

00:57:23.720 --> 00:57:26.770
[APPLAUSE]

